  "body": "#### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version: `1.7.2-stable`\r\nOS & Version: Linux\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\n\r\n--syncmode light should much faster than full mode since it only downloads the hash of blocks, and the space should be much smaller that full node.\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\nI'm testing light mode on Raspberry Pi 2,  connected to my private Ethereum network.\r\nOne uses light mode, the other one uses full mode.\r\nThe sync time seems similar, (But I **feel** the light mode was much faster on v1.7.1) the storage space is also similar.\r\nLight mode:\r\n```\r\npi@pi1:~/ethereum$ du -k\r\n4\t./keystore\r\n20\t./geth/chaindata\r\n197652\t./geth/lightchaindata\r\n452\t./geth/nodes\r\n58756\t./geth/ethash\r\n256888\t./geth\r\n256896\t.\r\n```\r\n\r\nFull mode:\r\n```\r\npi@pi2:~/ethereum$ du -k\r\n4\t./keystore\r\n286244\t./geth/chaindata\r\n20\t./geth/lightchaindata\r\n14224\t./geth/nodes\r\n58756\t./geth/ethash\r\n359252\t./geth\r\n359260\t.\r\n```\r\n\r\nSince this is a private network, so most blocks are empty (536 bytes), but I think hash of ~750,000\r\nblocks shouldn't use ~200Mbytes. that means one block hash occupied ~256 bytes. If so, then seems like full date uses ~286M is pretty good, since every block is 536 bytes, it supports to use ~400 Mybtes (536 * 750000).\r\n\r\n\r\n",
